data.title: The Theory Of Everything: Eddie Redmayne as Stephen Hawking? Pure Genius
data.meta_description: Film acting is said to be all in the eyes and that’s certainly true here: look into Redmayne’s eyes and it’s Hawking you see looking back. It’s quite astonishing.
data.text:
The Theory Of Everything

Cert: 12A 2hrs 3mins ★★★★★

I need to begin 2015 with an apology; to the lovely Anne Hathaway, no less, who I mocked for delivering this rather tortuous line in Christopher Nolan’s Interstellar: ‘Love is the one thing that we’re capable of perceiving that transcends dimensions of time and space.’

Well, that may not be quite what you want to hear when you’re struggling to stop your spaceship from falling into a black hole – as her co-star Matthew McConaughey was at the time – but it turns out she was absolutely right.

Because in The Theory Of Everything, a dramatisation of the life of the theoretical physicist and author of A Brief History Of Time Stephen Hawking, it is indeed love that transcends all the talk of both time and space – not to mention crippling physical illness – and makes this the most wonderful and quite unmissable start to the film year.

With both Bafta and Oscar nominations due to be announced over the next fortnight, expect this Working Title production to feature prominently. That’s astonishing because this is a film that really shouldn’t work at all.

After all, Hawking’s life has already been the subject of a rather good 2004 television film, Hawking – starring Benedict Cumberbatch, no less – and director Stephen Finnigan teamed up with the physicist himself to give us the documentary version – also called Hawking – just 16 months ago. There really shouldn’t be much more to say.

But because Ms Hathaway turned out to be right, because love really does transcend all the talk here of time, space, black holes and singularities, and because this is based not on Hawking’s own memoir but on that written by his first wife, Jane, there absolutely is.

This isn’t a film about cosmology or indeed the motor neurone disease Hawking was diagnosed with when he was just 21 years old; this is, first and foremost, a love story and a gorgeous one to boot.

It certainly gets the full romantic treatment from British director James Marsh – beautiful Cambridge settings, an immaculately polished script from Antony McCarten, and a sumptuous score from the Icelandic composer Jóhann Jóhannsson.

But most of all it has Eddie Redmayne and Felicity Jones in the central roles of Hawking and Jane Wilde, who are simply stunning together and totally enchanting.

Redmayne, in particular, surely slaying for ever the slur that he’s just another posh pretty boy, is an absolute revelation.

Yes, the tragic paradox that is Hawking’s life – the brilliant mind trapped inside a near-useless body – is something of a gift to a decent actor, but Redmayne – his head tilted questioningly to one side, his hair flopping messily forward – delivers it with the very lightest of touches.

He captures the physical mannerisms of the man, the strange mix of arrogance and shyness that first wins Jane over, and Hawking’s playful sense of humour.

‘I have a slight problem with the celestial dictatorship premise,’ he explains hesitantly as his ‘intelligent atheism’ meets Jane’s more engrained CofE.

Film acting is said to be all in the eyes and that’s certainly true here: look into Redmayne’s eyes and it’s Hawking you see looking back. It’s quite astonishing.

Jones is lovely too as Jane Wilde, very much the arts student to Hawking’s science graduate and a young woman who isn’t going to allow a diagnosis of what everyone assumed would be a swiftly terminal illness to get in the way of her love for her chosen young man.

Hawking’s own father warns her to think again: ‘This will not be a fight, Jane, this is going to be a very heavy defeat.’

But Jane will not be deterred. The couple are soon married, children are on their way and Hawking has begun his life’s work – to find ‘one simple, elegant equation that will explain everything’.

As I understand it (which isn’t a lot), the real-life Hawking, who celebrates his 73rd birthday next week, still hasn’t managed that but, despite the title, this film is not the place for possible shortcomings to be discussed.

This is a film primarily about Hawking’s surprisingly eventful personal life, not his professional career.

For Marsh – hitherto best known for the 2012 Northern Ireland thriller Shadow Dancer, and the strange chimpanzee documentary Project Nim – this is a big step up, but he’s certainly not intimidated, marshalling camera-work, editing and, above all, acting to fabulous effect.

In that respect, his success echoes that enjoyed by other up-and-coming directors with similar breakthrough films, such as Tom Hooper with The King’s Speech and Morten Tyldum with The Imitation Game.

It’s one of the few sadnesses of the impending awards seasons that The Theory Of Everything and The Imitation Game are going to be competing with each other for the top prizes.

Apart from the quality of the acting (look out for Simon McBurney as Hawking’s father and an excellent David Thewlis as his tutor and mentor, Dennis Sciama) what makes The Theory Of Everything such a watchable treat is its emotional balance.

We are never totally overwhelmed by the seemingly tragic arc of Hawking’s life.

There is always some hope lifting the despair, a little happiness to leaven the sadness – so a crashing fall in a Cambridge quad is matched by a wonderfully romantic slow-dance over the River Cam; an emergency tracheotomy by a very silly game of Daleks with his children.

And yet for all this light and shade, be warned the film contains one of the saddest break-up scenes you’ll ever see.

Love might transcend time and space, as Hathaway says, but it can’t, it seems, transcend everything. Wonderful.

SECOND SCREEN

Birdman

Cert: 15 1hr 59mins ★★★★★

Birdman is one of the most extraordinary films you’ll see all year, brilliantly acted, particularly by Michael Keaton in the central role, and technically… well, the word ‘dazzling’ just doesn’t do it justice.

You almost have to see it twice to fully appreciate what the Mexican director Alejandro Gonzalez Inarritu (who made Babel, 21 Grams and Amores Perros) and director of photography Emmanuel Lubezki (Gravity, enough said) have achieved.

As the camera stalks through the backstage corridors and dressing rooms of a Broadway theatre in the disaster-strewn days leading up to opening night, there are almost no discernible edits at all.

In this age of computer trickery that can’t quite be true but there are undoubtedly brilliantly organised, ingeniously choreographed continuous shots that go on more or less for ever. The word ‘cut’ just doesn’t seem to have been in Inarritu’s vocabulary.

But while this is terribly clever – almost to the point of showing off – there’s so much more to a film that signals its thought-provoking ambitions right from the opening shot, which sees Keaton, as actor Riggan Thomas, meditating in his dressing room.

He’s sitting cross-legged but floating in mid-air… which might be par for the course if we were watching Birdman, the fictional superhero Riggan used to play on television, rather than the actor himself.

But then this is a film – on one level about an ageing actor trying to shake off the long shadow of his high-ratings past and reinvent himself as a serious theatre thespian – where fact and fantasy, past and present are constantly getting mixed up.

Is Riggan levitating because he genuinely has superpowers, because he imagines he has them, or because that’s how his fans, unable to separate character from actor, see him? Don’t expect a simple answer.

Keaton whose own turn as a former Batman makes him perfect for the role, is vanity-free and nomination-grabbingly good.

There’s wonderful support from Edward Norton as the younger actor who challenges him, Zach Galifianakis as the agent trying to keep the show on the road, and Lindsay Duncan as the waspish critic who wants to close him down.

A must for anyone interested in the fleeting nature of fame, the cruelties of showbusiness and the astonishing things you can do with a Steadicam these days.

Oh, and the relentlessly percussive, unsettling score from Mexican drummer Antonio Sanchez is quite something too.

The Woman In Black: Angel Of Death

Cert: 15 1hr 38mins ★★★★★

Back in early 2012, Woman In Black had so much going for it – Susan Hill’s enduringly popular ghost story, Daniel Radcliffe and cracking direction from James Watkins – that it had audiences literally jumping in their seat.

It was always going to be a tough act to follow and so it proves as, 40 years on, a London girls’ school is evacuated to the same creepy old Eel Marsh House, where they discover the evil child-snatching spirit still very much in residence.

Phoebe Fox certainly catches the eye as the young teacher, and with all sorts of things going bump in the basement, the film does have its fair share of scares. But Hill’s story doesn’t altogether make sense – why would a school be evacuated to a house that is virtually derelict?

Also, some of the supporting characters struggle to convince and, frankly, we’ve all rather got the measure of the vengeful old biddy by now.

Enemy

Cert: 15 1hr 30mins ★★★★★

In Enemy Jake Gyllenhaal’s college lecturer Adam rents a DVD and discovers a bit-part actor (Gyllenhaal again) who looks just like him: an identical double.

Handily, he lives nearby.
